<exercises xml:id="s_nullspace_image_ex">
  <exercisegroup>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For each linear transformation <m>T</m> give parametric descriptions of <m>\NS T</m> and <m>\im T</m>. To do so you will want to relate each computation to a system of linear equations. (See <xref ref="eg_subspace_image"/> for an example of computing an image.)
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>T\colon \R^4 \amp \rightarrow \R^3 </mrow>
            <mrow> (x,y,z,w)\amp\mapsto (x+z+w, x-y-z,-2x+y-w) </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> T\colon M_{22}\amp \rightarrow M_{22} </mrow>
            <mrow> A \amp\mapsto \begin{amatrix}[rr]1\amp 1\\ 1\amp 1  \end{amatrix}A </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> T\colon P_2\amp \rightarrow P_2 </mrow>
            <mrow> f \amp\mapsto f(x)+f'(x)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <exercisegroup>
  <introduction>
  <p>
  For the given linear transformation <m>T</m> prove the claim about <m>\im T</m>.
  </p>
  </introduction>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>T\colon \R^\infty \amp \rightarrow \R^\infty </mrow>
          <mrow> s=(a_1,a_2,\dots)\amp\mapsto T(s)=(a_2,a_3,\dots) </mrow>
        </md>.
        Claim: <m>\im T=\R^\infty</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>T\colon C(\R) \amp \rightarrow C(\R) </mrow>
          <mrow> f(x)\amp\mapsto g(x)=f(x)+f(-x)</mrow>
        </md>.
        Claim: <m>\im T</m> is the set of all continuous symmetric functions. In other words,
        <me>
          \im T=\{f\in C(\R)\colon f(-x)=f(x)\}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Define <m>T\colon P_5\rightarrow \R^3</m> as <m>T(p(x))=(p(-2), p(3), p(7))</m>: <ie />, the value of <m>T</m> at the input polynomial <m>p(x)\in P_5</m> is computed by evaluating <m>p</m> at the inputs <m>x=-2,3,7</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove: <m>T</m> is a linear transformation.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove: the <m>W=\{p(x)\in P_5\colon p(-2)=p(3)=p(7)=0\}</m> is a subspace of <m>P_5</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Use <xref ref="proc_subspace_nullspace"/>.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>
<exercisegroup>
<introduction>
<p>
For each subset <m>W\subseteq V</m> show <m>W</m> is a subspace by identifying it with the null space of a linear transformation <m>T</m>. You may use any of the examples from <xref ref="s_transformation"/>, and any of the results from the exercises in <xref ref="s_transformation_ex"/>.
</p>
</introduction>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <me>
        W=\{A\in M_{nn}\colon \tr A=0\}
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <me>
        W=\{A\in M_{nn}\colon A^T=-A\}
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <me>
        W=\{f\in C^2(\R)\colon f''=2f'-3f\}
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>
<exercisegroup>
<introduction>
<p>
For each <m>m\times n</m> matrix <m>A</m> and vector <m>\boldb\in \R^m</m>:
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>
      Find a <em>particular</em> solution <m>\boldx_p</m> to <m>A\boldx=\boldb</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Find all solutions to the corresponding homogeneous matrix equation <m>A\boldx=\boldzero</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Use (a), (b), and <xref ref="cor_matrix_equations"/> to describe <em>all</em> solutions to <m>A\boldx=\boldb</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</p>
</introduction>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <me>
        A=\begin{amatrix}[rrrr]1\amp 2\amp 1\amp 1\\ 1\amp 1\amp 2\amp 3  \end{amatrix},
        \boldb=(3,2)
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <me>
        A=\begin{amatrix}[rrr]1\amp 1\amp -3 \\ 3\amp -1\amp -1 \\
        1\amp 0\amp -1  \end{amatrix},
        \boldb=(2,1,-4)
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      <me>
        A=\begin{amatrix}[rrr]1\amp 2\amp 1 \\ 1\amp 1\amp -3 \\ 1\amp 0\amp -1  \end{amatrix},
        \boldb=(1,1,1)
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>


</exercises>
